This is a log of outputs from routines in curves_tomita.py
The idea is to keep track of what Elliptic Curves I can build

q_res = make_quartic(QQ(20/-9), (QQ(49/318), QQ(23/106)))
model_quartic_as_elliptic_curve(q_res[2], QQ(-59/81))
Elliptic Curve defined by y^2 = x^3 + 2265722465761*x - 3154189403034549278 over Rational Field, 
which matches C1:X^3+2265722465761X-3154189403034549278=Y^2

Just five elliptic curves are responsible for 35, namely (10+12+5+4+4=35),
or more than third of known solutions, namely,
C0:X3-X2+2815805388X-94443526967868=Y2
C1:X3+2265722465761X-3154189403034549278=Y2
C5:X3+2639323244332897X-20156152630838819347102=Y2
C7:X3-X2+349942184229228X-11167797929528591502588=Y2
C9:X3-X2+9243195710310751148X-761969307339454319105751548=Y2
all with rank 3 and also discussed by Tomita.

C0 (u=-5/8) is the one studied by Elkies.
C1 (u=-9/20) yields the smallest d=422481, as well as the most d < bound.
C5 (u=-41/36) was found by the GDRZ team.
C7 (u=-5/44) is by Bremner.
C9 (u=-125/92) is also by Bremner, found in 2015.
